The {{nihongo|'''''Hobutsushu'''''|宝物集|"Collection of Treasures}} is a Japanese anthology of ''[[setsuwa]]'' stories compiled by the monk Tairano Yasuyori in 1179.

The stories take the form of a series of discussions between a [[Zen|Zen monk]] and an audience, and are intended to guide the reader towards [[satori]].<ref name="Kawashima2001">{{cite book|author=Terry Kawashima|title=Writing Margins: The Textual Construction of Gender in Heian and Kamakura Japan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KC807wsyLA0C&pg=PA116|accessdate=27 June 2012|year=2001|publisher=Harvard Univ Asia Center|isbn=978-0-674-00516-7|pages=115}}</ref> Among the subjects covered are the stories of [[Rama]], derived from Indian and Chinese sources,<ref name="Snodgrass2010">{{cite book|author=Mary Ellen Snodgrass|title=Encyclopedia of the Literature of Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LXyyYs2cRDcC&pg=PT254|accessdate=27 June 2012|date=12 May 2010|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-1906-9|pages=254}}</ref><ref name="Centre2002">{{cite book|author=India International Centre|title=India and east Asia: culture and society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=22ZuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=27 June 2012|date=1 January 2002|publisher=Shipra Publications|isbn=978-81-7541-106-7|page=156}}</ref> and the fate of [[Murasaki Shikibu]], whom Tairano condemns to hell for publishing fiction.<ref name="Shirane1987">{{cite book|author=Haruo Shirane|title=The Bridge of Dreams: A Poetics of the Tale of Genji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yOL3QataG7kC&pg=PR16|accessdate=27 June 2012|year=1987|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-1719-9|pages=16}}</ref>

