{{Infobox US Cabinet official | name=Michael Hillegas | image=Michael Hillegas (Engraved Portrait).jpg | caption = | order=1st | title=[[Treasurer of the United States]] | term_start=July 29, 1775 | term_end=September 11, 1789 | predecessor=Position established | successor=[[Samuel Meredith]] | president= | order2= | title2= | term_start2= | term_end2= | president2= | predecessor2= | successor2= | birth_date=April 22, 1729 | birth_place=[[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] | death_date={{Death date and age|1804|9|29|1729|4|22}} | death_place=[[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] | party= | spouse= | profession= | signature = Michael Hillegas signature.png | footnotes=Portrait engraved by GFC Smillie (artwork by A.M. Archambault). }} [[File:HILLEGAS, Michael (signed check).jpg|thumb|Check signed by Hillegas as Treasurer of the United States (1782).]] [[File:US $10 1907 Gold Certificate.jpg|thumb|right|1907 $10 gold certificate featuring Hillegas's portrait.]] '''Michael Hillegas''' (April 22, 1729 – September 29, 1804) was the first [[Treasurer of the United States]].<ref>[http://www.treas.gov/education/history/treasurers Treasurers of the United States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513211935/http://www.treas.gov/education/history/treasurers/ |date=2008-05-13 }}.</ref>
==Biography== Hillegas was born in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>[http://www.pgs.org/culture.asp Pennsylvania German Culture and History]</ref> He was the son of Margaret Schiebenstock (1710 – July 21, 1770) and George Michael Hillegass (February 14, 1696 – October 30, 1749), an immigrant from [[Germany]]<ref name="appletons">{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Hillegas, Michael|year=1892}}</ref> and a well-to-do merchant involved in iron and sugar. Soon Michael thus had the freedom and resources to participate in local politics. He married Henrietta Boude on May 10, 1753, at Christ Church in Philadelphia, and they went on to have many children. Hillegas was a member of the [[Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly]] from 1765 to 1775 and served as [[treasurer]] of the [[Committee of Safety (American Revolution)|Committee of Safety]] under [[Benjamin Franklin]] in 1774.
On July 29, 1775, Hillegas and fellow patriot [[George Clymer]] were appointed by the [[Continental Congress]] to share the office of Treasurer of the United Colonies.<ref>US Treasury website, [http://www.treas.gov/offices/treasurer/office-history.shtml History of the Treasurer's Office] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070508215131/http://www.treas.gov/offices/treasurer/office-history.shtml |date=2007-05-08 }}</ref> Because Hillegas edited the Declaration of Independence, when the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] was signed, Clymer's signature appeared on the document.
After Clymer's resignation on August 6, 1776, Hillegas assumed sole ownership of the office, which he held throughout the remainder of the [[American Revolution]], using much of his own fortune to support the cause. His son, Samuel Hillegas, was also given the authority to sign new currency, known as "Continentals." Hillegas also served briefly as quartermaster to the army and served on occasional commissions. On September 9, 1776, the Continental Congress officially changed the name of the country to the [[United States|United States of America]], but Hillegas's title did not officially change until March 1778. On September 11, 1789, Congress created the Treasury Department, and [[Alexander Hamilton]] took the oath of office as the first [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]]. On that same date, Hillegas tendered his resignation, and [[Samuel Meredith]] was appointed Treasurer.
Hillegas was also an early member of the [[American Philosophical Society]], along with Franklin. He died in Philadelphia and is buried near Franklin in [[Christ Church Burial Ground]]. Late in the 19th century, his descendants petitioned<ref>Rev. Michael Reed Minnich, ''A Memoir of the First Treasurer of the United States'', 1905.</ref> to have his portrait appear on the ten-dollar [[gold certificate]] in the series issued in the years 1907 and 1922.<ref>[[Gold certificate#Series and varieties]]</ref>
