{{Jainism}}
{{Contains special characters}}
'''''Samayasāra''''' (''The Nature of the Self'') is a famous [[Jain text]] composed by ''[[Kundakunda|Acharya Kundakunda]]'' in 439 verses.{{sfn|Jaini|1991|p=33}} Its ten chapters discuss the nature of ''[[Jīva (Jainism)|Jīva]]'' (pure self/soul), its attachment to [[Karma in Jainism|Karma]] and [[Moksha (Jainism)|Moksha]] (liberation). ''Samayasāra'' expounds the Jain concepts like ''[[Karma in Jainism|Karma]]'', ''[[Asrava]]'' (influx of ''karmas''), [[Bandha (Jainism)|Bandha]] (Bondage), ''[[Samvara]]'' (stoppage), ''[[Nirjara]]'' (shedding) and [[Moksha (Jainism)|Moksha]] (complete annihilation of ''karmas'').

Jainism says that shedding ''karmas'' i.e. getting rid of ''karmas'' leads to ''Moksha'' (liberation, salvation). ''Samayasāra'', in its ''Nirjara'' (shedding) chapter describes that shedding of ''karmas'' happens when a person observes both pleasant and unpleasant sensations without any ''Raag'' (attachment) and ''dveśa'' (aversion).

==Contents==

=== Invocation ===
The first verse ([[aphorism]]) of the ''Samayasāra'' is an invocation: {{quote|O bhavyas (potential aspirants to liberation)! Making obeisance to all the Siddhas, established in the fifth state of existence that is eternal, immutable, and incomparable (perfection par excellence), I will articulate this Samayaprābhrita, which has been propounded by the all-knowing Masters of Scripture.{{sfn|Jain|2012|p=1}}}}

===The Soul===
{{Main|Jīva (Jainism)}}
According to ''Samayasāra'', the real self is only that soul which has achieved [[ratnatraya]] i.e. Samyak Darshan, Samyak Gyan and Samyak Charitra. These state when soul achieves purity is [[Arihant (Jainism)|Arihant]] and [[Siddha]].{{sfn|Jain|2012|p=3}} It can be achieved by victory over five senses.

